1. Embedded Firmware (ESP32 - ESP-IDF)
The ESP32 is the heart of the hard real-time system. Implementing the dual-core architecture and I2S DMA will be the most complex software task.

Dual-Core Task Pinning:
Pin the UART receiving task to Core 0. Implement a robust Ringbuffer to ingest the 921,600 baud data without dropping frames.
Pin the Motion Control and Printhead Sync tasks to Core 1.
Gantry Implementation & Motion Control:
TMC2209 Interfacing: Implement UART configuration for the TMC2209s to set stealthChop, microstepping, and motor current.
Step/Dir Generation: Use the ESP32's MCPWM or RMT peripheral to generate smooth acceleration/deceleration profiles for the X, Y, and Z axes.
Homing Sequence: Implement limit switch interrupts for the homing sequence prior to printing.
Absolute Positioning (PCNT):
Configure the ESP32 Hardware Pulse Counter (PCNT) to read the 150 LPI optical encoder.
Create an interrupt or hardware trigger that links the PCNT threshold to the I2S DMA output.
I2S DMA Printhead Firing:
Configure the I2S peripheral in parallel LCD/Camera mode to blast the 42-byte chunks across 12 GPIO pins simultaneously.
Ensure the DMA descriptors are tightly synchronized with the encoder pulses so ink is deposited exactly on the grid, regardless of gantry speed fluctuations.
2. Backend (Raspberry Pi - Python/FastAPI/OpenCV)
The backend handles the "slower" but computationally heavy tasks.

Camera & Vision Pipeline:
Implement the OpenCV interface to capture the downward-facing camera feed.
Write the algorithm to allow users to set a bounding box around the nail.
Image Processing:
Curvature Mapping: Implement the 1D sine-wave pre-distortion algorithm to warp the 2D image so it prints correctly over the 3D curvature of the nail.
Halftoning: Implement the Floyd-Steinberg error diffusion algorithm to convert the RGB image into a binary CMYK matrix suitable for the HP 63 cartridge.
Serial Communication:
Implement a high-performance Python serial loop (using pyserial) to chunk the CMYK matrix into 42-byte payloads and stream them to the ESP32 over USB at 921,600 baud. Implement software flow control (ACK/NACK) to prevent buffer overflows on the ESP32.
3. Frontend (React/Vue via Vite)
The kiosk UI needs to be intuitive for a touchscreen environment.

Kiosk Interface:
Build a full-screen, touch-optimized UI.
Create a live video feed component showing the finger under the camera.
Print Setup & Controls:
Implement touch-and-drag controls for the bounding box / image cropping over the live feed.
Add a design selection menu (gallery of images to print).
Implement a state machine UI (Idle -> Calibrating -> Ready -> Printing -> Done).
Backend Communication:
Use WebSockets or REST endpoints to communicate with the FastAPI backend to start/stop prints and fetch progress.
4. Hardware & PCB Design (Signal Integrity Focus)
Based on your README, the split between the Mainboard and the Smart Carriage is highly effective for reducing inductive ringing. However, several critical checks are required before fabrication:

Smart Carriage Signal Integrity:
The 3.3V data lines traveling over the Flexible Flat Cable (FFC) from the ESP32 to the CD4504B level shifters on the carriage are highly susceptible to crosstalk and EMI from the stepper motor wires. Ensure the FFC has interlaced ground lines (e.g., Signal, GND, Signal, GND).
Ensure decoupling capacitors (0.1µF) are placed immediately next to the power pins of the CD4504B on the carriage.
Hardware Failsafe (Guillotine):
Verify the RC time-constant of the AC-coupled gate drive (capacitive differentiator). A 10-15µs timeout is extremely tight. Ensure the chosen capacitor and resistor values account for component tolerances (typically ±5% or ±10%) so it doesn't accidentally cut off legitimate 5µs firing pulses.
Power Distribution Network (PDN):
The 24V to 16V, 9V, and 5V step-downs will generate heat and switching noise. Ensure the buck converters have appropriate LC output filters.
Isolate the 5V logic plane from the 24V motor plane as much as possible using split ground planes tied at a single star point.
5. Integration & Calibration
Hand-Eye Calibration:
Implement the routine mentioned in the README to map camera pixel coordinates to physical stepper steps. This likely requires printing a calibration grid, capturing it with the camera, and calculating the homography matrix.
Print Timing Tuning:
Use a logic analyzer to verify that the ESP32 is actually generating exactly 5µs pulses. An HP thermal inkjet will quickly burn out if the firing pulse duration is inaccurate.
Recommended Next Steps (Action Plan)
Before writing UI code or routing PCBs, I recommend tackling the highest-risk technical challenges first:

Bench-test the Printhead Firing: Hook up the ESP32, the level shifters, and the discrete MOSFET array to an oscilloscope/logic analyzer. Verify you can reliably generate the 5µs pulses across 12 pins using I2S DMA. Do not connect the actual ink cartridge until this is verified.
Bench-test the Hardware Failsafe: Force a GPIO pin HIGH permanently and use the oscilloscope to ensure the capacitive differentiator successfully severs the 16V line after 10-15µs.
Prototype the Vision Pipeline: Write a standalone Python script to test the sine-wave warping and Floyd-Steinberg dithering on a static image to ensure the output matrix looks correct before integrating it with FastAPI.